input.prompt:
I'm debugging why clicking a story paragraph in ChapterReader doesn't highlight it. We just implemented a fix that adds a `.pcl-active` CSS class via JS, but it's not working. I need to identify all root causes and design the fix.

## Current Code State

### CSS (ChapterReader.css, relevant lines):
```css
/* Line 177: desktop hover highlight */
.chapter-reader-content .editor-paragraph[data-paragraph-index]:hover {
    background-color: var(--bg-selection);
}

/* Line 268: our new pcl-active rule */
.chapter-reader-content .editor-paragraph.pcl-active {
    background-color: var(--bg-selection);
}

/* Line 273: mobile media query */
@media (max-width: 768px) {
    .pcl-badge { padding: 4px 6px; font-size: 0.64rem; }

    /* Line 279: override hover to transparent on mobile */
    .chapter-reader-content .editor-paragraph[data-paragraph-index]:hover {
        background-color: transparent;
    }
}
```

### JS (ParagraphCommentLayer.jsx):
- `clickedRef` is set to `true` in the paragraph click handler
- `leave` handler skips `scheduleLeave` when `clickedRef.current` is true
- `useEffect` watches `hoveredIndex` and toggles `.pcl-active` class on matching paragraph
- Separate `useEffect` registers document click listener to dismiss when clicking outside

## Issues Found

### Issue 1: CSS Specificity Bug (PRIMARY)
On mobile, the `:hover` transparent rule has HIGHER specificity than `.pcl-active`:
- `.chapter-reader-content .editor-paragraph[data-paragraph-index]:hover` = **0-4-0** (3 classes/attrs + 1 pseudo-class)
- `.chapter-reader-content .editor-paragraph.pcl-active` = **0-3-0** (3 classes)

When a mobile user taps, the browser applies `:hover` state. Since the transparent rule has higher specificity, it overrides pcl-active's background. On many mobile browsers, `:hover` persists until the next tap, so the highlight NEVER shows.

### Issue 2: `handleBadgeLeave` doesn't check `clickedRef`
```jsx
const handleBadgeLeave = useCallback((idx, event) => {
    // ... checks relatedTarget ...
    scheduleLeave(idx);  // ← fires even if clickedRef is true!
}, [scheduleLeave]);
```
After clicking a paragraph (locking it), if the cursor passes over the badge and leaves, `handleBadgeLeave` calls `scheduleLeave`, clearing the highlight after 450ms. It should respect `clickedRef` like the paragraph leave handler does.

### Issue 3: Outside-click listener not registered after mouseenter→click sequence
The outside click effect depends on `hoveredIndex`:
```jsx
useEffect(() => {
    if (!clickedRef.current) return;
    // register document click listener
}, [hoveredIndex, containerRef]);
```
On desktop: mouseenter already sets `hoveredIndex` to `idx`. When the user then clicks, `setHoveredIndex(idx)` is the same value — React skips the re-render. The effect doesn't re-run. If `clickedRef` was false when the effect ran during mouseenter, the listener was never registered. The user can never dismiss by clicking outside.

## DOM Structure (from ChapterReader.jsx)
```
.chapter-reader-body (bodyRef = containerRef)
  ├── LexicalComposer (editable: false)
  │    └── ContentEditable.chapter-reader-content
  │         └── .editor-paragraph elements
  └── ParagraphCommentLayer (.pcl-layer)
```

Please design a minimal fix for all 3 issues. Focus on the simplest correct changes.

